Setup
Motivation
  • Setting up everything we need
Tools
  • Visual Studio: You need either Visual Studio IDE or Visual Studio Code
  • I haven’t tried VS Code on Windows…If you do choose this one, let me know how it goes!
  • Link: https://visualstudio.microsoft.com/
  • Note: You will need to register VS (free) to keep using it past 30 days:
  • Make sure you select “Desktop development with C++” so you get the C++ tools
  • The installer takes a long time to run…You can move on while it cranks away
SDL
  • Fetch SDL (you might already have these files from last semester)
  • Win64 binaries: http://www.libsdl.org/release/SDL2-devel-2.0.10-VC.zip
SDL
  • Unzip the SDL zipfile somewhere
    • NOT in the folder where you’ll be storing your project code!
    • You’ll notice there are header files (.h), compiler libraries (.lib) and runtime libraries (.dll)
  • We’ll need each of these in a bit…
Path
  • Add the folder with SDL.dll to your PATH
  • First, click start and type “control panel”
Path
  • Change to small icon view and choose “User Accounts”
Path
  • Choose “Change my environment variables”
Path
  • If you already have a variable called “Path” (capitalization doesn’t matter), choose it and click “Edit”
  • If you don’t have a variable called “Path,” choose “New”
Path
  • Note that sometimes (for reasons I haven’t figured out), Windows will give you a nice edit box
  • Other times, it gives you the unfriendly text box as shown
Path
  • The value should be the location where the SDL DLL file is located
  • If there are already items in the PATH variable, add a semicolon and then the SDL folder
  • Ex: c:\Program Files\foo;c:\program files (x86)\bar;c:\users\bobdesktop\libraries
  • If you have another SDL folder already mentioned in PATH (ex: From last semester), I’d suggest you clear it out
New Project
  • We’re ready to start a project
New Project
  • Start Visual Studio
  • Create a new project
Project
  • Choose Visual C++, Windows Desktop, Windows Console Application
Platform
  • Choose x64 from the toolbar
Junk
  • Visual Studio created some template files, but we don’t need them
  • They will be named “stdafx.cpp”, “stdafx.h”, “targetver.h”, and one more that will depend on what you named your project
  • Right click each of the four and choose “Remove” to tidy things up
Framework
  • From the class webpage, get the lab framework
    • This is the solution to the last lab from 2801 ported to C++
  • Unzip the file
  • You’ll notice there are several folders:
    • assets (Art assets)
    • shaders (Shaders. Duh.)
    • h (C++ header files)
    • cpp (C++ source files)
    • utils (miscellaneous things that you probably won’t need)
  • Make sure the things in the zip file are directly inside your project directory
    • In other words, side-by-side with Visual Studio’s .sln file
Add
  • Right click “Source Files” and choose Add → Existing Item…
Add
  • Change the type dropdown to “Visual C++ files” and select all the cpp files
Add
  • Right click “Header Files” and add the header files (from the h directory)
Properties
  • Right click the project name and choose “Properties”
Properties
  • Choose Debugging (left side pane)
  • Set the “Working Directory” field to
    $(SolutionDir)
Properties
  • Choose “VC++ Directories”
Properties
  • Under “Include Directories” click the drop-down and choose “Edit”
  • Add an entry for the SDL2 include folder (where the .h files are)
  • Add an entry for the h folder that you just expanded from the framework zipfile
Properties
  • Under “Library Directories” add an entry for the SDL2 library folder (where the .lib files are)
Properties
  • Under “Source Directories” add an entry for the cpp folder you got from the framework zipfile
Properties
  • Under C/C++ → Precompiled Headers:
    • Set “Precompiled Header” to “Not using precompiled headers”
Properties
  • Select C/C++ → Preprocessor
  • Select “Edit” for “Preprocessor Definitions”
Properties
  • Ensure these things are in the list:
    • WIN32
    • _DEBUG
    • _WINDOWS
    • _CONSOLE
    • _CRT_SECURE_NO_WARNINGS
    • NOMINMAX
Properties
  • Choose Linker → Input. Edit the “Additional Dependencies” item
Properties
  • Put these items in “Additional Dependencies”:
    • SDL2.lib
    • SDL2main.lib
    • windowscodecs.lib
That’s It!
  • If everything was set up correctly, you should be able to run the program now!
Assignment
  • Turn in a screenshot of the program running on your computer
    • This is to show that you really did get it running!
